  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and conventions aimed at combating money laundering. Some key examples include:\n\n1. The Financial Action Task Force (FATF) recommendations\n- Sets global standards for preventing money laundering\n- Provides guidelines for national legal and regulatory systems\n\n2. United Nations Convention Against Transnational Organized Crime\n- Requires member states to criminalize money laundering\n- Promotes international cooperation in investigating financial crimes\n\n3. The Palermo Convention\n- Provides framework for international cooperation against organized crime\n- Includes provisions for tracking and preventing money laundering\n\n4. Basel Committee's Anti-Money Laundering (AML) principles\n- Establishes guidelines for banking institutions\n- Promotes transparency in financial transactions\n\n5. EU Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Provides regulations for European financial institutions\n- Requires customer due diligence and reporting of suspicious activities\n\nMost countries have domestic laws implementing these international standards, requiring financial institutions to:\n- Verify customer identities\n- Report suspicious transactions\n- Maintain transaction records\n- Implement compliance programs\n\nThese laws aim to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds as legitimate income.",
